Baselines:
1.1. There used to be a Working Committee in 2011-2012 to link the interests of both institutions.  During this period, the committee issued four joint regulations to manage the code of conduct of judges.  Currently, there is no bridging unit to mediate any tensions between the two institutions. This situation underpins the importance of having a working unit that can bridge and nurture a good relationship between the two institutions.

1.2 The current workload of the High Court in the area of supervision is quite immense and faces many difficulties.  Furthermore, the current internal oversight procedure places a financial burden on the High Court which must provide funding to three Bawas members in Jakarta to travel to relevant regions for reporting reasons.   Under the revised draft bill of the Supreme Court law, the High Court is mandated to provide funding to one Bawas member only as well as two High Court oversight judges.  The change will result in savings for the High Court and improve the performance of Bawas because all 40 (forty) of its members can handle more reports;

High Court supervisory judges who should function as a bridge between the Supreme Court and district courts have been facing some constraints which hamper their duties, such as lack of staff and capacity gaps among personnel, limited budget allocations to conduct supervision, the absence of a special unit in the High Court that is responsible for conducting supervision,  and lack of standard procedures to do their duties;   

Bawas is subject to E-Audit from the Supreme Audit Board (BPK).  However Bawas, for various reasons, cannot apply a similar survey.   Bawas has also worked on the internal complaints mechanism for whistle blowers;  
Some aspects of the baseline survey implementation on judicial public service in the appointed regions need to be reviewed and refined according to recent developments. Survey implementation in the appointed regions has only been conducted once

